data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the EF Core Cosmos DB provider allowed synchronous LINQ via an opt-in (`CosmosOptionsExtension` / sync-over-async configuration). **In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** The Cosmos provider is now async-only.

Every sync call in your repository will throw **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime:

- `ToList()` → ❌
- `First()` → ❌
- `Count()` → ❌
- `SaveChanges()` → ❌

## The Fix

Convert to fully async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Return `Task<T>` / `Task`, mark methods `async`
2. Replace sync LINQ operators with `*Async` counterparts
3. `await` each call
4. Rename methods (convention: `*Async` suffix)

Callers up the chain must also become async — this typically propagates up to controller actions, which ASP.NET Core already supports as `async Task<IActionResult>`.
